            reviewDate: 'August 15, 2022',
            semester: 'summer 2022',
            review: "This was my ninth course in the OMSCS program.  I took it during the Summer 2022 term.  Having got past the hurdle of Graduate Algorithms, my sanity needed a breather.  I chose this class for that reason... that, and I am a software developer by profession.  Therefore, I feel any software class where I at least learn something is a win for my career.  This class consists of some quizzes, an individual project, a team project, discussion forum participation, and completion of Canvas module quizzes.  There is a lot of focus on diagrams and the software process in general.  Instead of percentages, a total points scale (1000) is used.\nCoursework\n\nPractice Quizzes: These consist of the Canvas quizzes covering the material in each module.  You can take them over and over until you receive full points.  While they do not directly count towards your grade, they are a part of the participation grade.  It is very tedious, time-consuming, and frustrating having to take some quizzes 5+ times until you get all available points.  You must continue taking these until you get a perfect score as thy do play a part in your participation score\nQuizzes (150 points): There are 6 quizzes in the class.  The lowest grade of the quizzes is dropped.  They are open everything (except fellow students and googling the answer).  You have 1 hour to take them in Canvas, and they are not proctored.  You are given a guide early in the class as to what material will be covered in the quiz.  You are allowed 2 attempts, with the highest score counting.  It is easy to review the quiz and better prepare yourself for the second attempt if you have to retake it.\nAssignments (725 points): These consist of various processes throughout the software design process.  Assignment 1 was to create a UML diagram based on a spec which was provided.  Assignment 2 was to review 3 diagrams provided to you and provide feedback.  Assignment 3 was to implement the program identified as part of A1 and A2.  The spec for this was very vague, and a lot of inferences and Ed posts are necessary to understand what is really being asked.  Assignment 4 is the start of the team project.  It requires taking the program discussed in A1-A3, adding some functional and non-functional requirements, create some new documentation, and update existing ones.  Assignment 5 is for the team to take the program from A3 and implement these functional and non-functional requirements, generate more new documents, update the documents from A4 as the code evolves, and record videos to submit.  Assignment 6 is purely a placeholder for the CATME survey/evaluation of yourself and your teammembers.\nParticipation (125 points): This consisted of 3 parts: Ed participation, group project feedback, and lecture/module quizzes.  For the participation points, you had to submit meaningful posts and replies on Ed.  This had to be more than an \"I agree\", or \"good point.\"  Many people used it to ask lost of questions about UML diagramming and questions about the assignments.  The practice quizzes mentioned above are also a part of this grade.  While the grades on those quizzes do not count directly to these points, completing all the practice quizzes with a perfect score was all but required.  Lastly, your team's feedback on your group project played a huge role in these points.  Make sure you are on a good team, be a good team player, and be sure your team knows your contributions to the success of the project.\n\nTake-Aways\n\n\nMiscellaneous Stuff: Not having to worry about exams is a plus.  I despise them.  I am not the biggest fan of a points system, but in the end, it is a wash with a percentage system.  For the points system, A: 900-1000, B:800-899, C:700-199, D: 600-699, F: 0-599.  The turnaround time on assignments is horrendous.  A3 was due on 27 June 2022, but grades for it were released on 22 July 2022... almost a month later.  Part of the A3 assignment was code they ran through an autograder, so not really sure whey they couldn't have done that and got those grades to us while they worked on grading the documentation.  When I got my A3 grades, I had to constantly send an Ed message to the TA team to get feedback as they failed to upload comments on my submissions, which reduced the amount of time I had to determine if I wanted to make a regrade request or not.\n\n\nQuizzes:\n\nThe practice quizzes are mind-numbing.  Some of them you have to take over and over and over until you get a perfect score.  While they don't count towards your grade, they are an essential part of the participation grade.\nThe graded quizzes cover specific material from a given week(s) lecture and reading material.  The assignment quiz guide they provide at the beginning of the course outlines what material will be on what quiz.\n\n\n\nLectures: The lectures are from when the class was created in the past.  The instructor is pretty much reading off the slides.  It is like being in a classroom where the professor purely reads off the slides and isn't free-thinking.  It all feels too scripted.  The lectures where the professor is trying to have a conversation with someone about a task is enough to put you to sleep as it definitely feels scripted.  The content could be really good if it was updated; however, it is mediocre, dry, and boring, which is a perfect combination to lose interest.\n\n\nTextbook: There is no textbook required.\n\n\nProjects: The individual project was broken into 3 Assignments (take a spec and create the UML class diagram, evaluate 3 other student's diagrams with the spec and give meaningful feedback, and implementing the program based on the spec).  The team project built on top of the individual project by introducing functional and non-functional requirements, required creating new and updating existing documentation, implementing the program based on the spec and changes to the spec, and evaluating the contributions of your team members.\n\n\nExams:  There are no exams.\n\n\nProfessor and TAs: The entire teaching staff was great.  Matt and Pablo do a great job with feedback in Ed.  They step in only to re-align incorrect statements, answer when no one else has answered, or confirm a student's reply.  They really try to let the students help each other instead of just coming in and answering all the questions.  This gives students ample time to work on those participation points.\n\n\nExtra Credit: There was an opportunity for some extra credit.  The professors started everyone off with 10 points of extra credit, which evaluates to 1% being added to your final grade.  There were stipulations, though.  Anytime someone requested to have their CATME team member evaluation reopened because they didn't follow instructions, everyone lost 0.4 points of the 10 available points until the value reached 0.  So, anytime anyone made a post on the thread, everyone lost points from the extra credit points, regardless if you followed instructions or not.  This allows for 25 re-open requests, and they get used up quickly, even with people asking when their survey would be reopened.\n\n\nOverall Grade: I put an acceptable amount of time in this course (over 146 hours to be exact).  In the end, my grade was 96.4, which got me an A.  At the end of the course, I saw an A was posted to my transcript, but it wasn't until 7 days after grades are due to the registrar that I saw my grades for Assignment 5, Assignment 6, and Participation.\n\n\nTLDR\nThis class is pretty much straightforward and somewhat easy.  The course is designed to focus on the diagramming and designing of software.  As such, don't expect a lot of programming.  Be sure to get all those participation points.  Find a good team.  Look past the painful monotony of the lectures and practice quizzes.  Prepare to wait and wait and wait for grades and feedback... like, expect some grades to appear in Canvas after the course ends and grades are required to be submitted to the registrar for your transcript.",
